  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions involves several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed historically\n- Emerged as a significant legal concept in the 20th century\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - first major anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Criminalized currency transaction reporting violations\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- Introduced international standards for combating money laundering\n- Encouraged global cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n4. Key Legislation Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed comprehensive international standards\n- Created recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n6. Modern Approach:\n- Increasingly sophisticated detection mechanisms\n- Expanded coverage to digital currencies\n- Strong emphasis on international collaboration\n\nThese developments reflect a progressive legal approach to combating financial crimes through increasingly comprehensive regulatory mechanisms.",
